Question 1

The data dat1 consists of an explanatory variable x and a binary response variable Y. Using this data, duplicate the plots exactly.

Note: To create the GLM line, you will need to create a set of points using equation:

\[ f(x) = \frac{e^{0.2+0.07x}}{1+e^{0.2+0.07x}} \] Then you can use the lines() function.

Answers

load("dat1.Rdata")
f = function(x){
  y = exp(0.2+0.07*x) / (1+exp(0.2+0.07*x))
  return (y)
}
par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar=c(3,2.5,2.5,1), mgp = c(3, 0.4, 0), tck = -0.02)

# Graph 1
barplot(table(dat1$Y), col = c("black", "red"),
        ylim = c(0, 30), cex.axis = 0.6, cex.names = 0.7, las = 0)
title("Distribution of Variable Y", cex.main = 0.8)
box()

# Graph 2
plot(dat1$Y~dat1$X, xlab = "", ylab = "", cex = 0.4, pch = 19, las = 0, cex.axis = 0.6, 
     xlim = c(-50, 50), ylim = c(0, 1))
title("Plot of X vs Y", cex.main = 0.8)
mtext("X", side = 1, line = 1.5, cex = 0.6)
mtext("Y", side = 2, line = 1.5, cex = 0.6)
abline(lm(Y~X, data = dat1), col = "red", lty = 3)
lines(seq(-60, 60, 1), f(seq(-60, 60, 1)), col = "blue")
legend("topleft", c("OLS Line", "GLM Line"), 
       lty = c(3, 1), col = c("red", "blue"), 
       cex = 0.6)

Question 2

The data dat2 consists of z which is 100 randomly generated normal values, and t which is 100 randomly generated t values. Using this data, create the following plots exactly.

To draw the normal curves in the histogram, you will need to use the dnorm() function. Use the sample means and sample standard deviations for the parameters of the curves.

Answers

load("dat2.Rdata")

par(mfrow = c(2, 2), mar=c(3,2.5,2.5,1), mgp = c(3, 0.4, 0), tck = -0.02)

# Graph 1
hist(dat2$z, freq = F, breaks = 26, col = "yellow",
     cex.axis = 0.7, main = "")
curve(dnorm, -3, 3, add = T)
title("Histogram of Random Normal Variables", cex.main = 0.9)
mtext("Random Normal Variables", side = 1, line = 1.5, cex = 0.6)
mtext("Density", side = 2, line = 1.5, cex = 0.6)
abline(h=0)

# Graph 2
hist(dat2$t, freq = F, breaks = 30, col = "green", 
     cex.axis = 0.7, main = "", xlim = c(-10, 10))
curve(dnorm(x, mean = mean(dat2$t), sd = sd(dat2$t)), -11, 11, add = T)
title("Histogram of Random t Variables", cex.main = 0.9)
mtext("Random t Variables", side = 1, line = 1.5, cex = 0.6)
mtext("Density", side = 2, line = 1.5, cex = 0.6)
abline(h=0)

# Graph 3
boxplot(dat2[,1:2], names = c("Normal", "t"),
        cex = 0.4, pch = 19, col = c("yellow", "green"), cex.axis = 0.7)
title("Comparison of Random Normal and Random t Data", cex.main = 0.9)

Question 3

The data dough is the data for the dough-rising experiment from the SAS midterm. Using this data, create the following plot exactly.

Answers

load("dough.Rdata")
par(mfrow = c(1, 1), mar=c(4,4,3.2,2), mgp = c(3, 0.6, 0), tck = -0.02)

plot(NA, NA, xlim = c(60, 80), ylim = c(20, 34), 
     xlab = "", ylab = "", main = "", cex.axis = 0.7) 
points(dough$Temperature[dough$Additive==1], dough$RisingTime[dough$Additive==1],
       pch = 20, col = "red", cex = 0.6)
points(dough$Temperature[dough$Additive==2], dough$RisingTime[dough$Additive==2],
       pch = 20, col = "green", cex = 0.6)
points(dough$Temperature[dough$Additive==3], dough$RisingTime[dough$Additive==3],
       pch = 20, col = "blue", cex = 0.6)
points(dough$Temperature[dough$Additive==4], dough$RisingTime[dough$Additive==4],
       pch = 20, col = "black", cex = 0.6)

title("Affect of Temperature on Rising Time by Additive", cex.main = 0.95)
mtext("Temperature", side = 1, line = 1.9, cex = 0.8)
mtext("RisingTime", side = 2, line = 1.9, cex = 0.8)
legend("topleft", c("Gluten", "Barley", "Potato", "None"), 
       col = c("red", "green", "blue", "black"), pch = 20, cex = 0.75)

Question 4

The data pittsburg consists of the hourly temperature in Pittsburg on 22 July 2013. Using this data, create the following plot exactly.

Answers

pittsburg = read.table("pburgjuly22.txt")

par(mfrow = c(1, 1), mar=c(4,4,3.2,2), mgp = c(3, 0.6, 0), tck = -0.02)

plot(pittsburg$V2, type = "b", cex = 0.6, pch = 1,
     main = "", xlab = "", ylab = "", axes = F)
title("Hourly Temperature for Pittsburg", cex.main = 0.95)
mtext("Hour", side = 1, line = 1.9, cex = 0.9)
mtext("Temperature in Farenheit", side = 2, line = 1.9, cex = 0.9)
axis(1, at = seq(1, 22, 3), 
     label = paste(rep(c(12, 3, 6, 9), times = 2), rep(c("AM", "PM"), each = 4), sep = ""),
     cex.axis = 0.7)
axis(2, at = seq(66, 78, 2), labels = T, cex.axis = 0.7, las = 0)
box()
